events.description: The teenaged Edward III is crowned King of England, but the country is ruled by his mother Queen Isabella and her lover Roger Mortimer.
events.html: • 1327 – The teenaged Edward III is crowned King of England, but the country is ruled by his mother Queen Isabella and her lover Roger Mortimer.[1]

events.description: The First Peace of Thorn is signed in Thorn (Toruń), Monastic State of the Teutonic Knights (Prussia).
events.html: • 1411 – The First Peace of Thorn is signed in Thorn (Toruń), Monastic State of the Teutonic Knights (Prussia).[2]

entities.name: Monastic State of the Teutonic Knights

events.description: The Chinese general Koxinga seizes the island of Taiwan after a nine-month siege.
events.html: • 1662 – The Chinese general Koxinga seizes the island of Taiwan after a nine-month siege.[3]

events.description: The Kalabalik or Skirmish at Bender results from the Ottoman sultan's order that his unwelcome guest, King Charles XII of Sweden, be seized.
events.html: • 1713 – The Kalabalik or Skirmish at Bender results from the Ottoman sultan's order that his unwelcome guest, King Charles XII of Sweden, be seized.[4]

events.description: French Revolutionary Wars: France declares war on the United Kingdom and the Netherlands.
events.html: • 1793 – French Revolutionary Wars: France declares war on the United Kingdom and the Netherlands.

events.description: The capital of Upper Canada is moved from Newark to York.
events.html: • 1796 – The capital of Upper Canada is moved from Newark to York.

events.description: Mayon in the Philippines erupts, killing around 1,200 people, the most devastating eruption of the volcano.
events.html: • 1814 – Mayon in the Philippines erupts, killing around 1,200 people, the most devastating eruption of the volcano.

events.description: Slavery is abolished in Mauritius.
events.html: • 1835 – Slavery is abolished in Mauritius.[5]

events.description: American Civil War: Texas secedes from the United States and joins the Confederacy a week later.
events.html: • 1861 – American Civil War: Texas secedes from the United States and joins the Confederacy a week later.

entities.name: Texas in the American Civil War

events.description: Second Schleswig War: Prussian forces crossed the border into Schleswig, starting the war.
events.html: • 1864 – Second Schleswig War: Prussian forces crossed the border into Schleswig, starting the war.[6]

events.description: President Abraham Lincoln signs the Thirteenth Amendment to the United States Constitution.
events.html: • 1865 – President Abraham Lincoln signs the Thirteenth Amendment to the United States Constitution.

entities.name: Thirteenth Amendment to the United States Constitution

events.description: The first volume (A to Ant) of the Oxford English Dictionary is published.
events.html: • 1884 – The first volume (A to Ant) of the Oxford English Dictionary is published.[7]

events.description: Thomas A. Edison finishes construction of the first motion picture studio, the Black Maria in West Orange, New Jersey.
events.html: • 1893 – Thomas A. Edison finishes construction of the first motion picture studio, the Black Maria in West Orange, New Jersey.[8]

events.description: Fountains Valley, Pretoria, the oldest nature reserve in Africa, is proclaimed by President Paul Kruger.
events.html: • 1895 – Fountains Valley, Pretoria, the oldest nature reserve in Africa, is proclaimed by President Paul Kruger.

events.description: La bohème premieres in Turin at the Teatro Regio (Turin), conducted by the young Arturo Toscanini.
events.html: • 1896 – La bohème premieres in Turin at the Teatro Regio (Turin), conducted by the young Arturo Toscanini.

events.description: Shinhan Bank, the oldest bank in South Korea, opens in Seoul.
events.html: • 1897 – Shinhan Bank, the oldest bank in South Korea, opens in Seoul.

entities.name: List of banks in South Korea

events.description: Great Britain, defeated by Boers in key battles, names Lord Roberts commander of British forces in South Africa.
events.html: • 1900 – Great Britain, defeated by Boers in key battles, names Lord Roberts commander of British forces in South Africa.[9]

events.description: Lisbon Regicide: King Carlos I of Portugal and Infante Luis Filipe are shot dead in Lisbon.
events.html: • 1908 – Lisbon Regicide: King Carlos I of Portugal and Infante Luis Filipe are shot dead in Lisbon.[10]

entities.name: Luís Filipe, Prince Royal of Portugal

events.description: Russia–United Kingdom relations are restored, over six years after the Communist revolution.
events.html: • 1924 – Russia–United Kingdom relations are restored, over six years after the Communist revolution.[11]

events.description: World War II: Josef Terboven, Reichskommissar of German-occupied Norway, appoints Vidkun Quisling the Minister President of the National Government.
events.html: • 1942 – World War II: Josef Terboven, Reichskommissar of German-occupied Norway, appoints Vidkun Quisling the Minister President of the National Government.

events.description: World War II: U.S. Navy conducts Marshalls–Gilberts raids, the first offensive action by the United States against Japanese forces in the Pacific Theater.
events.html: • 1942 – World War II: U.S. Navy conducts Marshalls–Gilberts raids, the first offensive action by the United States against Japanese forces in the Pacific Theater.[12]

entities.name: Pacific Ocean theater of World War II

events.description: Voice of America, the official external radio and television service of the United States government, begins broadcasting with programs aimed at areas controlled by the Axis powers.
events.html: • 1942 – Voice of America, the official external radio and television service of the United States government, begins broadcasting with programs aimed at areas controlled by the Axis powers.[13]

entities.name: Federal government of the United States

events.description: Mao Zedong makes a speech on "Reform in Learning, the Party and Literature", which puts into motion the Yan'an Rectification Movement.
events.html: • 1942 – Mao Zedong makes a speech on "Reform in Learning, the Party and Literature", which puts into motion the Yan'an Rectification Movement.[14]

events.description: Trygve Lie of Norway is picked to be the first United Nations Secretary-General.
events.html: • 1946 – Trygve Lie of Norway is picked to be the first United Nations Secretary-General.[15]

events.description: The Parliament of Hungary abolishes the monarchy after nine centuries, and proclaims the Hungarian Republic.
events.html: • 1946 – The Parliament of Hungary abolishes the monarchy after nine centuries, and proclaims the Hungarian Republic.[16]

events.description: The first prototype of the MiG-17 makes its maiden flight.
events.html: • 1950 – The first prototype of the MiG-17 makes its maiden flight.[17]

events.description: Northeast Airlines Flight 823 crashes on Rikers Island in New York City, killing 20 people and injuring 78 others.
events.html: • 1957 – Northeast Airlines Flight 823 crashes on Rikers Island in New York City, killing 20 people and injuring 78 others.[18]

events.description: Four black students stage the first of the Greensboro sit-ins at a lunch counter in Greensboro, North Carolina.
events.html: • 1960 – Four black students stage the first of the Greensboro sit-ins at a lunch counter in Greensboro, North Carolina.[19]

events.description: The Beatles have their first number one hit in the United States with "I Want to Hold Your Hand".
events.html: • 1964 – The Beatles have their first number one hit in the United States with "I Want to Hold Your Hand".[20]

entities.name: I Want to Hold Your Hand

events.description: Vietnam War: The execution of Viet Cong officer Nguyễn Văn Lém by South Vietnamese National Police Chief Nguyễn Ngọc Loan is recorded on motion picture film, as well as in an iconic still photograph taken by Eddie Adams.
events.html: • 1968 – Vietnam War: The execution of Viet Cong officer Nguyễn Văn Lém by South Vietnamese National Police Chief Nguyễn Ngọc Loan is recorded on motion picture film, as well as in an iconic still photograph taken by Eddie Adams.[21]

events.description: Canada's three military services, the Royal Canadian Navy, the Canadian Army and the Royal Canadian Air Force, are unified into the Canadian Forces.
events.html: • 1968 – Canada's three military services, the Royal Canadian Navy, the Canadian Army and the Royal Canadian Air Force, are unified into the Canadian Forces.[22]

events.description: The New York Central Railroad and the Pennsylvania Railroad are merged to form Penn Central Transportation.
events.html: • 1968 – The New York Central Railroad and the Pennsylvania Railroad are merged to form Penn Central Transportation.

events.description: Kuala Lumpur becomes a city by a royal charter granted by the Yang di-Pertuan Agong of Malaysia.
events.html: • 1972 – Kuala Lumpur becomes a city by a royal charter granted by the Yang di-Pertuan Agong of Malaysia.[23]

events.description: A fire in the 25-story Joelma Building in São Paulo, Brazil kills 189 and injures 293.
events.html: • 1974 – A fire in the 25-story Joelma Building in São Paulo, Brazil kills 189 and injures 293.

events.description: Iranian Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini returns to Tehran after nearly 15 years of exile.
events.html: • 1979 – Iranian Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini returns to Tehran after nearly 15 years of exile.[24]

events.description: The Underarm bowling incident of 1981 occurred when Trevor Chappell bowls underarm on the final delivery of a game between Australia and New Zealand at the Melbourne Cricket Ground (MCG).
events.html: • 1981 – The Underarm bowling incident of 1981 occurred when Trevor Chappell bowls underarm on the final delivery of a game between Australia and New Zealand at the Melbourne Cricket Ground (MCG).[25]

entities.name: New Zealand men's national cricket team

events.description: A runway collision between USAir Flight 1493 and SkyWest Flight 5569 at Los Angeles International Airport results in the deaths of 34 people, and injuries to 30 others.
events.html: • 1991 – A runway collision between USAir Flight 1493 and SkyWest Flight 5569 at Los Angeles International Airport results in the deaths of 34 people, and injuries to 30 others.[26]

events.description: A magnitude 6.8 earthquake strikes the Hindu Kush region, killing at least 848 people in Afghanistan, Pakistan and present-day Tajikistan.
events.html: • 1991 – A magnitude 6.8 earthquake strikes the Hindu Kush region, killing at least 848 people in Afghanistan, Pakistan and present-day Tajikistan.[27]

events.description: The Chief Judicial Magistrate of Bhopal court declares Warren Anderson, ex-CEO of Union Carbide, a fugitive under Indian law for failing to appear in the Bhopal disaster case.
events.html: • 1992 – The Chief Judicial Magistrate of Bhopal court declares Warren Anderson, ex-CEO of Union Carbide, a fugitive under Indian law for failing to appear in the Bhopal disaster case.[28]

events.description: The Communications Decency Act is passed by the U.S. Congress.
events.html: • 1996 – The Communications Decency Act is passed by the U.S. Congress.[29]

events.description: Rear Admiral Lillian E. Fishburne becomes the first female African American to be promoted to rear admiral.
events.html: • 1998 – Rear Admiral Lillian E. Fishburne becomes the first female African American to be promoted to rear admiral.[30]

events.description: Daniel Pearl, American journalist and South Asia Bureau Chief of The Wall Street Journal, kidnapped on January 23, is beheaded and mutilated by his captors.
events.html: • 2002 – Daniel Pearl, American journalist and South Asia Bureau Chief of The Wall Street Journal, kidnapped on January 23, is beheaded and mutilated by his captors.[31]

events.description: Space Shuttle Columbia disintegrated during the reentry of mission STS-107 into the Earth's atmosphere, killing all seven astronauts aboard.
events.html: • 2003 – Space Shuttle Columbia disintegrated during the reentry of mission STS-107 into the Earth's atmosphere, killing all seven astronauts aboard.[32]

events.description: Hajj pilgrimage stampede: In a stampede at the Hajj pilgrimage in Saudi Arabia, 251 people are trampled to death and 244 injured.
events.html: • 2004 – Hajj pilgrimage stampede: In a stampede at the Hajj pilgrimage in Saudi Arabia, 251 people are trampled to death and 244 injured.[33]

events.description: Double suicide attack in Erbil on the offices of Iraqi Kurdish political parties by members of Jama'at al-Tawhid wal-Jihad
events.html: • 2004 – Double suicide attack in Erbil on the offices of Iraqi Kurdish political parties by members of Jama'at al-Tawhid wal-Jihad[34]

events.description: King Gyanendra of Nepal carries out a coup d'état to capture the democracy, becoming Chairman of the Councils of ministers.
events.html: • 2005 – King Gyanendra of Nepal carries out a coup d'état to capture the democracy, becoming Chairman of the Councils of ministers.[35]

events.description: The National Weather Service in the United States switches from the Fujita scale to the new Enhanced Fujita scale to measure the intensity and strength of tornadoes.
events.html: • 2007 – The National Weather Service in the United States switches from the Fujita scale to the new Enhanced Fujita scale to measure the intensity and strength of tornadoes.[36]

events.description: The first cabinet of Jóhanna Sigurðardóttir was formed in Iceland, making her the country's first female prime minister and the world's first openly gay head of government.
events.html: • 2009 – The first cabinet of Jóhanna Sigurðardóttir was formed in Iceland, making her the country's first female prime minister and the world's first openly gay head of government.[37]

events.description: Seventy-four people are killed and over 500 injured as a result of clashes between fans of Egyptian football teams Al Masry and Al Ahly in the city of Port Said.
events.html: • 2012 – Seventy-four people are killed and over 500 injured as a result of clashes between fans of Egyptian football teams Al Masry and Al Ahly in the city of Port Said.[38]

events.description: The Shard, the sixth-tallest building in Europe, opens its viewing gallery to the public.
events.html: • 2013 – The Shard, the sixth-tallest building in Europe, opens its viewing gallery to the public.[39]

entities.name: List of tallest buildings in Europe

events.html: • 2021 – A coup d'état in Myanmar removes Aung San Suu Kyi from power and restores military rule.[40]
